{"actual_usd":0.12633,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":261,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24483,"reply":"\"No, I don't think it fizzled.\" *I hook one flour-dusted thumb into my apron and glance toward the bakery window, where the light's gone warm on the sill.* \"It feels more like bread set to rise than bread pulled from the oven too soon. The real thing has happened — truly happened — but there is still time in between the leaven going in and the loaf being ready to break.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through as the oven gives off its steady heat.* \"If Christ rose, then death's been dealt its mortal wound already. That isn't a rehearsal. That's the turning of the whole dough. But the kingdom coming fully...\" *I lift one shoulder a little.* \"Seems to me that's the part we're still living inside — the proving drawer, maybe. Not fake. Not stalled. Just unfinished in the way a promise can be underway before it's complete.\"\n\n\"I think that's why the world still feels so stubborn some days. We're not waiting to see whether Easter worked. We're waiting for what began there to finish arriving everywhere.\" *I look back at you, a little more directly.* \"Which part catches in your throat most — the waiting itself, or the fact that so much still looks unrisen?\"","rolling_24h_usd":92.03554499999998,"run_id":"375950a3-0cfa-4ec3-962c-eef15e4efdbc"}
